27. Ra8 {White wants to play Rh8 and starts attacking Black's kingside pawns.
What should Black do?} Rc1 {Black found a beautiful way to start his
counterattack. Usually, we are not attacking the king in the endgame, but
White loses a very important time hunting the h6-pawn. For that reason, Black
has time to organize his pieces against White's king.} 28. Rh8 b4 29. Rxh6 (29.
Nf3 $1 {It was the last chance to bring another defender.} -- 30. Nd2) 29...
Ka5 {Black is threatening mate in 2. White can capture another pawn, on f6,
but the rook and the knight cannot protect their king. The king is the most
important piece because if we lose the king, we lose the game...} 30. Ka2 (30.
-- Ba4+ 31. Ka2 b3#) 30... b3+ 31. Kxb3 Ba4+ 32. Ka2 Kb4 {This is another
characteristic playing style. Black's pieces are dominating in the queenside
and White cannot avoid the checkmate.} 33. b3 Bxb3+ 34. Kb2 Rd1 {
Black is winning.} 35. Bb1 Rd2+ 36. Ka1 (36. Kc1 Kc3 37. Nf3 Rd1# (37... Ba3#))
36... Kc3 (36... Kc3 37. Rxf6 Ba3 38. Rxf7 Bb2#) 0-1

